ce:section.ce:para:
Further increase of N-CQDs content in the hybrid thin film (c) with the nominal ratio (1.2 x10-3
                        ) of N-CQDs/ZnO (%(w/v)) enhances the band-edge UV emission (peaked at around 391 nm) and broadens its range in the similar way with the slight increase in the FWHM of 45 nm, ascertaining the non-radiative energy transfer from the incorporated N-CQDs to ZnO nanoparticles. The slightly increased PL emission in the visible range of hybrid film (c) when compared to that of film (b) is ascribed to the increased content of N-CQDs and their contribution of characteristic emission in the visible region. The significant reduction in the defect-related visible emission of hybrid thin films when compared to that of pristine ZnO (film a) corroborates the formation of size-controlled ZnO nanoparticles with decreased defect density upon increasing N-CQDs content in the hybrid thin films. In this study, the observed results reveal that the incorporated N-CQDs essentially get adsorbed (chemisorption) at the grain boundaries of ZnO crystallites and control its size in nanoscale, resulting in the improved film quality and facilitating the possible energy transfer between N-CQDs and ZnO in the hybrid films. Upon the UV (325 nm) excitation of N-CQDs/ZnO hybrid thin films, the incorporated N-CQDs adsorbed onto the surface of ZnO nanoparticles absorb the UV energy and not only facilitate its characteristic PL emission in the visible region through the different radiative pathways present in N-CQDs but also non-radiatively transfer the absorbed UV energy to ZnO efficiently, causing the enhanced band-edge (UV) emission of ZnO for increasing N-CQDs content in the hybrid thin films. The schematic representation of the formation of N-CQDs/ZnO hybrid thin films, the observed visible emission of N-CQDs, and enhanced UV band-edge emission of ZnO are depicted in the Fig. 10
                        . These results show that the hydrothermally synthesized N-CQDs incorporated sol–gel derived spin-coated ZnO (N-CQDs/ZnO) hybrid thin films will be very much useful for the solution-processed organic/hybrid optoelectronic devices such as OLEDs, OPVs, OTFTs, Sensors, and UV photodetectors.
